First, we simplify the expression for $\frac{15!}{6!(15-6)!}$:
\begin{align*}
\frac{15!}{6!9!} &= \frac{15 \cdot 14 \cdot 13 \cdot 12 \cdot 11 \cdot 10 \cdot 9!}{6! \cdot 9!} \\
&= \frac{15 \cdot 14 \cdot 13 \cdot 12 \cdot 11 \cdot 10}{6 \cdot 5 \cdot 4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2} \\
&= \frac{15 \cdot 14 \cdot 13 \cdot 12 \cdot 11 \cdot 10}{720} \\
&= 15 \cdot 14 \cdot 13 \cdot 12 \cdot 11 \cdot 10 / 720 \\
&= \boxed{5005}
\end{align*}

Second, we assess the number of ways to arrange 6 items. This is a permutation problem and the calculation for 6 items arranged in a row is $6!$, which is:
\begin{align*}
6! &= 6 \cdot 5 \cdot 4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1 \\
&= 720
\end{align*}

Conclusion:
The value of $\frac{15!}{6!(15-6)!}$ is $\boxed{5005}$. The number of ways to arrange 6 items in a row is $720$.

